                                        <measure type="textblockLeaves" quantity="24" unit="folios"/>
                                    </extent>
                                </supportDesc>
                                <layoutDesc>
                                    <layout columns="1" writtenLines="28">
                                        <locus from="3r" to="24v" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <dimensions type="written">
                                            <height quantity="105" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="65" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                        <note>Guidelines in ink.</note>
                                    </layout>
                                </layoutDesc>
                            </objectDesc>
                            <handDesc>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-1">
                                    <locus from="2v" to="23r" scheme="folios"/>Hybrida.</handNote>
                                <handNote xml:id="hand-2">
                                    <locus from="24v" to="24v" scheme="folios"/>Gothic cursive.</handNote>
                            </handDesc>
                            <additions>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Centre page, in brown ink by a 19th century hand: <quote>Ammoniciones ad vitam Spiritualem</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="2r" to="2r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>The page is filled with writing samples or pen-trials by a medieval hands. The samples consists of extracts from Luke 12, the phrase: <quote>vade semper mori mors numquam a te recedat</quote> (written twice), and: <quote>Incipiunt ammoniciones ad uitam spiritualem</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="Note_1" to="Note_1" scheme="other"/>
                                    <note>This little fragment, which carries text written by a medieval hand, was found between <locus from="1v" to="2r" scheme="folios"/>. It is now stored in an evelope.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="4r" to="22r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Scattered short additions or corrections, nota marks and crosses by several medieval hands.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="23r" to="23r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Lower part of page, an addition in brown in by an early modern hand. The addition is an excerpt from Johannes Trithemius's De scriptoribus ecclesiasticis. Above this addition the following note has been added by a different early modenr hand: <quote>Nota contra eos qui libellum Gerso Italo asseribunt</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="23v" to="23v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Top of page, two additions in black ink by a medieval or early modern hand: <quote>omnia ad maiorem</quote>; <quote>maria Inmaculate concepta</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="24r" to="24r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Top margin, in faded black ink: two initials, possibly mirrored.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="24v" to="24v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Below the main text in black ink by a medieval hand: <quote>AVdi filia et vide et inclina aurem tuam obliuiscere populum tuum domum patris tui concupisset</quote>. The text is smudged, perhaps an attempt at erasure (these lines are the same as the first lines on <locus from="25r" to="25r" scheme="folios"/>).</note>
                                </p>
                            </additions>
                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in black ink, rubrics in red, capitals touched in red.</p>
                                <decoNote type="initials">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="3r" to="3r" scheme="folios"/>: opening plain initial Q with interior reserved shapes over 7 lines in blue. The countersapce is filled with a vegetative shape in red and blue ink. The same type of shape also forms a frame around the intial, which extends into the margin. In the lower margin there are three floral shapes in red and blue. On the body of the initial the letters w a a w have been written in black ink. Additions in black ink are also found in the counterspace and in the decoration in the lower margin. These are most likely later additions. <locus from="3v" to="20v" scheme="folios"/>: plain chapter initials over 3 lines in red.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                            </decoDesc>
                        </physDesc>
